</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Tumors and tumorlike lesions that secondarily involve the mesothelial or submesothelial layers of the peritoneum are a diverse group of disorders that range in biologic behavior from benign to highly malignant. The anatomy of peritoneal ligaments and mesenteries and the normal circulation of peritoneal fluid dictate location and distribution of these diseases within the peritoneal cavity. Peritoneal carcinomatosis is the most common secondary tumor to affect the peritoneal cavity. When it arises from carcinomas of the gastrointestinal tract or ovary, the prognosis is grave. However, when low-grade mucinous adenocarcinoma of the appendix spreads to the peritoneal cavity, the consequence is typically pseudomyxoma peritonei, which is a clinical syndrome, characterized by recurrent and recalcitrant voluminous mucinous ascites due to surface growth on the peritoneum without significant invasion of underlying tissues. Carcinomas from elsewhere in the body, as well as lymphomas and sarcomas, may also produce diffuse peritoneal metastasis. Granulomatous peritonitis is the consequence of disseminated infection such as tuberculosis or histoplasmosis, foreign materials, or rupture of a tumor or hollow viscus. Finally, a group of benign miscellaneous conditions that range from common disorders such as endometriosis and splenosis to very rare conditions such as gliomatosis peritonei and melanosis may also affect the peritoneum diffusely. Secondary tumors and tumorlike lesions of the peritoneum have overlapping imaging features when compared with each other and primary peritoneal tumors. Knowledge of peritoneal anatomy, normal fluid circulation within the peritoneal cavity, and clinical and pathologic features of secondary peritoneal lesions is essential for identification of these lesions.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.292085189">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.292085189">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c01a.jpeg" height="1280" width="963" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Intraabdominal spaces formed by posterior peritoneal reflections. <b>(a)</b> Illustration of the normal posterior peritoneal reflections and intraabdominal spaces shows the cut surface of the transverse mesocolon (arrow), which divides the peritoneum into supramesocolic and inframesocolic compartments. The root of the small bowel mesentery (arrowhead) divides the inframesocolic compartment into the right and left infracolic spaces. The cut surface of the sigmoid mesentery is also shown. The sigmoid mesentery serves as a watershed to channel peritoneal fluid into the pelvis. <b>(b)</b> Illustration shows the pathways of flow of intraperitoneal fluid and the four predominant sites (<b>*</b>) of stasis of ascitic fluid in the lower abdomen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c01b.jpeg" height="1280" width="979" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Intraabdominal spaces formed by posterior peritoneal reflections. <b>(a)</b> Illustration of the normal posterior peritoneal reflections and intraabdominal spaces shows the cut surface of the transverse mesocolon (arrow), which divides the peritoneum into supramesocolic and inframesocolic compartments. The root of the small bowel mesentery (arrowhead) divides the inframesocolic compartment into the right and left infracolic spaces. The cut surface of the sigmoid mesentery is also shown. The sigmoid mesentery serves as a watershed to channel peritoneal fluid into the pelvis. <b>(b)</b> Illustration shows the pathways of flow of intraperitoneal fluid and the four predominant sites (<b>*</b>) of stasis of ascitic fluid in the lower abdomen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g02a.jpeg" height="1235" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Peritoneal carcinomatosis from adenocarcinoma of the colon in a 36-year-old man who complained of diffuse abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a small amount of ascites, nodular soft-tissue thickening of the right subdiaphragmatic peritoneum (arrows in <b>a</b>), and soft tissue infiltrating the greater omentum (arrows in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected greater omentum shows tumor nodules that stud the omental surface and replace normal fat. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain) shows that the peritoneum contains infiltrating glands of metastatic adenocarcinoma (arrows) with a dense desmoplastic stromal response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g02b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Peritoneal carcinomatosis from adenocarcinoma of the colon in a 36-year-old man who complained of diffuse abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a small amount of ascites, nodular soft-tissue thickening of the right subdiaphragmatic peritoneum (arrows in <b>a</b>), and soft tissue infiltrating the greater omentum (arrows in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected greater omentum shows tumor nodules that stud the omental surface and replace normal fat. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain) shows that the peritoneum contains infiltrating glands of metastatic adenocarcinoma (arrows) with a dense desmoplastic stromal response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c02c.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F2C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2c.</b>  Peritoneal carcinomatosis from adenocarcinoma of the colon in a 36-year-old man who complained of diffuse abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a small amount of ascites, nodular soft-tissue thickening of the right subdiaphragmatic peritoneum (arrows in <b>a</b>), and soft tissue infiltrating the greater omentum (arrows in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected greater omentum shows tumor nodules that stud the omental surface and replace normal fat. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain) shows that the peritoneum contains infiltrating glands of metastatic adenocarcinoma (arrows) with a dense desmoplastic stromal response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F2C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c02d.jpeg" height="787" width="1101" aria-labelledby="F2D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2d.</b>  Peritoneal carcinomatosis from adenocarcinoma of the colon in a 36-year-old man who complained of diffuse abdominal pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast material–enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show a small amount of ascites, nodular soft-tissue thickening of the right subdiaphragmatic peritoneum (arrows in <b>a</b>), and soft tissue infiltrating the greater omentum (arrows in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the resected greater omentum shows tumor nodules that stud the omental surface and replace normal fat. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain) shows that the peritoneum contains infiltrating glands of metastatic adenocarcinoma (arrows) with a dense desmoplastic stromal response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F2D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c03a.jpeg" height="915" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Peritoneal carcinomatosis from mucinous adenocarcinoma of the colon in a 14-year-old boy who complained of abdominal pain and increasing abdominal girth. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows tumor cells floating in pools of mucin; one signet ring cell has a large cytoplasmic mucin droplet, which displaces the nucleus to the periphery of the cell (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse sonogram of the pelvis shows a large amount of ascites that contains fixed echoes and nodular, sheetlike thickening of the posterior peritoneum (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g03b.jpeg" height="1305" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Peritoneal carcinomatosis from mucinous adenocarcinoma of the colon in a 14-year-old boy who complained of abdominal pain and increasing abdominal girth. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows tumor cells floating in pools of mucin; one signet ring cell has a large cytoplasmic mucin droplet, which displaces the nucleus to the periphery of the cell (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Transverse sonogram of the pelvis shows a large amount of ascites that contains fixed echoes and nodular, sheetlike thickening of the posterior peritoneum (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g04a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Colonic adenocarcinoma with peritoneal carcinomatosis in a 41-year-old man who complained of bloody stools. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT images show the primary lesion in the transverse colon (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>) with pericolonic lymphadenopathy; nodular peritoneal thickening in the left upper quadrant (arrow in <b>a</b>); and tumor nodules in the gastrosplenic ligament (arrow in <b>b</b>), left paracolic gutter (arrow in <b>c</b>), and retrovesical space (arrow in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g04b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Colonic adenocarcinoma with peritoneal carcinomatosis in a 41-year-old man who complained of bloody stools. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT images show the primary lesion in the transverse colon (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>) with pericolonic lymphadenopathy; nodular peritoneal thickening in the left upper quadrant (arrow in <b>a</b>); and tumor nodules in the gastrosplenic ligament (arrow in <b>b</b>), left paracolic gutter (arrow in <b>c</b>), and retrovesical space (arrow in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g04c.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  Colonic adenocarcinoma with peritoneal carcinomatosis in a 41-year-old man who complained of bloody stools. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT images show the primary lesion in the transverse colon (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>) with pericolonic lymphadenopathy; nodular peritoneal thickening in the left upper quadrant (arrow in <b>a</b>); and tumor nodules in the gastrosplenic ligament (arrow in <b>b</b>), left paracolic gutter (arrow in <b>c</b>), and retrovesical space (arrow in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g04d.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4d.</b>  Colonic adenocarcinoma with peritoneal carcinomatosis in a 41-year-old man who complained of bloody stools. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT images show the primary lesion in the transverse colon (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>) with pericolonic lymphadenopathy; nodular peritoneal thickening in the left upper quadrant (arrow in <b>a</b>); and tumor nodules in the gastrosplenic ligament (arrow in <b>b</b>), left paracolic gutter (arrow in <b>c</b>), and retrovesical space (arrow in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F4D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g05a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Peritoneal mucinous carcinomatosis that caused small bowel obstruction in a 40-year-old man who complained of progressive abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show low-attenuation mucinous ascites that infiltrates between the folds of the small bowel mesentery. There are low-attenuation mucinous metastatic deposits in the greater omentum (arrows in <b>a</b>) and soft-tissue attenuation deposits along the peritoneal surfaces and in the paracolic gutters (arrows in <b>b</b>). The small bowel is partially obstructed from metastatic tumor that encases a segment of distal small bowel (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g05b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Peritoneal mucinous carcinomatosis that caused small bowel obstruction in a 40-year-old man who complained of progressive abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show low-attenuation mucinous ascites that infiltrates between the folds of the small bowel mesentery. There are low-attenuation mucinous metastatic deposits in the greater omentum (arrows in <b>a</b>) and soft-tissue attenuation deposits along the peritoneal surfaces and in the paracolic gutters (arrows in <b>b</b>). The small bowel is partially obstructed from metastatic tumor that encases a segment of distal small bowel (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g06a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Peritoneal carcinomatosis from ovarian carcinoma in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows loculated ascites. <b>(b)</b> Fused PET/CT image shows focal, intense uptake in the left mid abdomen (arrow) from a peritoneal metastatic deposit that is nearly isoattenuating relative to the ascites and difficult to visualize with CT alone. (Case courtesy of Aaron L. Stack, MD, Walter Reed Army Medical Center, Washington, DC.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c06b.jpeg" height="915" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Peritoneal carcinomatosis from ovarian carcinoma in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows loculated ascites. <b>(b)</b> Fused PET/CT image shows focal, intense uptake in the left mid abdomen (arrow) from a peritoneal metastatic deposit that is nearly isoattenuating relative to the ascites and difficult to visualize with CT alone. (Case courtesy of Aaron L. Stack, MD, Walter Reed Army Medical Center, Washington, DC.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c07a.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Pathologic features of pseudomyxoma peritonei, low-grade mucinous neoplasm on peritoneal surfaces. <b>(a)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows globules of mucin adherent to the greater omentum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×20; H-E stain) shows well-differentiated, orderly glandular cells that line the peritoneal surface without invading the stroma. The cells with globoid mucinous cytoplasm are the source of the abundant extracellular mucin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c07b.jpeg" height="915" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Pathologic features of pseudomyxoma peritonei, low-grade mucinous neoplasm on peritoneal surfaces. <b>(a)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows globules of mucin adherent to the greater omentum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×20; H-E stain) shows well-differentiated, orderly glandular cells that line the peritoneal surface without invading the stroma. The cells with globoid mucinous cytoplasm are the source of the abundant extracellular mucin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g08a.jpeg" height="1268" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei in a 70-year-old woman who complained of increasing abdominal girth. Longitudinal <b>(a)</b> and transverse <b>(b)</b> sonograms of the abdomen show complex, hypoechoic ascites that contains nonmobile echoes and centrally displaced small bowel that has a starburst appearance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g08b.jpeg" height="1270" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei in a 70-year-old woman who complained of increasing abdominal girth. Longitudinal <b>(a)</b> and transverse <b>(b)</b> sonograms of the abdomen show complex, hypoechoic ascites that contains nonmobile echoes and centrally displaced small bowel that has a starburst appearance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g09a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei in a 50-year-old man who complained of increasing abdominal girth, fatigue, and malaise. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show low-attenuation mucinous ascites that scallops the margins of the liver, spleen, and gastric fundus; displaces bowel and mesentery; and contains coarse calcifications. The greater omentum (arrow in <b>b</b>) has increased attenuation from omental infiltration or fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g09b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei in a 50-year-old man who complained of increasing abdominal girth, fatigue, and malaise. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show low-attenuation mucinous ascites that scallops the margins of the liver, spleen, and gastric fundus; displaces bowel and mesentery; and contains coarse calcifications. The greater omentum (arrow in <b>b</b>) has increased attenuation from omental infiltration or fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g10a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei in a 47-year-old man who complained of a 6-month history of early satiety, weight loss, and abdominal distention. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show a 5-cm low-attenuation cystic dilatation of the appendix in the right lower quadrant (arrow in <b>b</b>), mucin infiltrating the omentum, nodular thickening of the falciform ligament, and mucinous ascites that scallops the margin of the liver. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the cut surface of the resected appendix reveals mural thickening and hemorrhagic, nodular mucin globules in the lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g10b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei in a 47-year-old man who complained of a 6-month history of early satiety, weight loss, and abdominal distention. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show a 5-cm low-attenuation cystic dilatation of the appendix in the right lower quadrant (arrow in <b>b</b>), mucin infiltrating the omentum, nodular thickening of the falciform ligament, and mucinous ascites that scallops the margin of the liver. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the cut surface of the resected appendix reveals mural thickening and hemorrhagic, nodular mucin globules in the lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c10c.jpeg" height="808" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei in a 47-year-old man who complained of a 6-month history of early satiety, weight loss, and abdominal distention. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show a 5-cm low-attenuation cystic dilatation of the appendix in the right lower quadrant (arrow in <b>b</b>), mucin infiltrating the omentum, nodular thickening of the falciform ligament, and mucinous ascites that scallops the margin of the liver. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the cut surface of the resected appendix reveals mural thickening and hemorrhagic, nodular mucin globules in the lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g11a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei from an appendiceal mucinous cystadenoma in a 51-year-old woman who was being evaluated for ovarian masses that were causing urinary frequency. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show well-defined, complex, cystic adnexal masses that extend into the upper abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pouch of Douglas <b>(b)</b>. A small amount of low-attenuation fluid is seen in the right paracolic gutter. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows an enlarged, distended appendix (arrow) with extruding mucin (arrowheads). On the basis of histologic features, the lesion involving the appendix was diagnosed to be a ruptured mucinous cystadenoma. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows bilateral ovarian masses that were histologically consistent with secondary involvement from the ruptured appendiceal mucinous “cystadenoma,” perhaps better termed low-grade mucinous neoplasm because of its secondary ovarian growth.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g11b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei from an appendiceal mucinous cystadenoma in a 51-year-old woman who was being evaluated for ovarian masses that were causing urinary frequency. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show well-defined, complex, cystic adnexal masses that extend into the upper abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pouch of Douglas <b>(b)</b>. A small amount of low-attenuation fluid is seen in the right paracolic gutter. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows an enlarged, distended appendix (arrow) with extruding mucin (arrowheads). On the basis of histologic features, the lesion involving the appendix was diagnosed to be a ruptured mucinous cystadenoma. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows bilateral ovarian masses that were histologically consistent with secondary involvement from the ruptured appendiceal mucinous “cystadenoma,” perhaps better termed low-grade mucinous neoplasm because of its secondary ovarian growth.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c11c.jpeg" height="839" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F11C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11c.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei from an appendiceal mucinous cystadenoma in a 51-year-old woman who was being evaluated for ovarian masses that were causing urinary frequency. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show well-defined, complex, cystic adnexal masses that extend into the upper abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pouch of Douglas <b>(b)</b>. A small amount of low-attenuation fluid is seen in the right paracolic gutter. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows an enlarged, distended appendix (arrow) with extruding mucin (arrowheads). On the basis of histologic features, the lesion involving the appendix was diagnosed to be a ruptured mucinous cystadenoma. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows bilateral ovarian masses that were histologically consistent with secondary involvement from the ruptured appendiceal mucinous “cystadenoma,” perhaps better termed low-grade mucinous neoplasm because of its secondary ovarian growth.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F11C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c11d.jpeg" height="840" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F11D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11d.</b>  Pseudomyxoma peritonei from an appendiceal mucinous cystadenoma in a 51-year-old woman who was being evaluated for ovarian masses that were causing urinary frequency. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show well-defined, complex, cystic adnexal masses that extend into the upper abdomen <b>(a)</b> and pouch of Douglas <b>(b)</b>. A small amount of low-attenuation fluid is seen in the right paracolic gutter. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows an enlarged, distended appendix (arrow) with extruding mucin (arrowheads). On the basis of histologic features, the lesion involving the appendix was diagnosed to be a ruptured mucinous cystadenoma. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows bilateral ovarian masses that were histologically consistent with secondary involvement from the ruptured appendiceal mucinous “cystadenoma,” perhaps better termed low-grade mucinous neoplasm because of its secondary ovarian growth.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F11D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c12a.jpeg" height="841" width="1178" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Lymphomatosis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×2; H-E stain) shows a relatively monomorphous, slightly nodular, lymphoid infiltrate that distorts the normal peritoneum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×20; H-E stain) shows the lymphoid cells, which are medium sized and irregularly shaped. Scattered, larger, atypical cells with vesicular nuclei and nucleoli are also present. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows soft tissue diffusely infiltrating through the peritoneum, encasing the small bowel, and lining the folds of the small bowel mesentery. Ascites and diffuse peritoneal thickening are present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c12b.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Lymphomatosis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×2; H-E stain) shows a relatively monomorphous, slightly nodular, lymphoid infiltrate that distorts the normal peritoneum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×20; H-E stain) shows the lymphoid cells, which are medium sized and irregularly shaped. Scattered, larger, atypical cells with vesicular nuclei and nucleoli are also present. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows soft tissue diffusely infiltrating through the peritoneum, encasing the small bowel, and lining the folds of the small bowel mesentery. Ascites and diffuse peritoneal thickening are present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g12c.jpeg" height="1238" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12c.</b>  Lymphomatosis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×2; H-E stain) shows a relatively monomorphous, slightly nodular, lymphoid infiltrate that distorts the normal peritoneum. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×20; H-E stain) shows the lymphoid cells, which are medium sized and irregularly shaped. Scattered, larger, atypical cells with vesicular nuclei and nucleoli are also present. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows soft tissue diffusely infiltrating through the peritoneum, encasing the small bowel, and lining the folds of the small bowel mesentery. Ascites and diffuse peritoneal thickening are present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F12C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g13a.jpeg" height="1199" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Gastrointestinal stromal tumor metastatic to the peritoneum. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show a metastatic deposit of tumor on the serosal surface of the liver (arrow in <b>a</b>) and a large, partially cystic metastatic deposit in the left mid abdomen (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>). No significant ascites is present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g13b.jpeg" height="1201" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Gastrointestinal stromal tumor metastatic to the peritoneum. Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans show a metastatic deposit of tumor on the serosal surface of the liver (arrow in <b>a</b>) and a large, partially cystic metastatic deposit in the left mid abdomen (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>). No significant ascites is present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c14a.jpeg" height="786" width="1101" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Tuberculous peritonitis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) shows a caseating granuloma with a central area of necrotic acellular debris surrounded by histiocytes, some of which are multinucleated (arrow), and a variable number of lymphocytes. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; acid-fast bacillus [Ziehl-Neelsen] stain) reveals barely visible tuberculous organisms (arrows), which appear as small, thin, red bacilli. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan of a 22-year-old man who complained of intermittent fevers for 1 month and a new onset of abdominal pain shows loculated ascites. There is diffuse enhancement of the peritoneum and nodularity of the greater omentum (arrow). The visualized small bowel segments are fixed with mild dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c14b.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Tuberculous peritonitis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) shows a caseating granuloma with a central area of necrotic acellular debris surrounded by histiocytes, some of which are multinucleated (arrow), and a variable number of lymphocytes. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; acid-fast bacillus [Ziehl-Neelsen] stain) reveals barely visible tuberculous organisms (arrows), which appear as small, thin, red bacilli. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan of a 22-year-old man who complained of intermittent fevers for 1 month and a new onset of abdominal pain shows loculated ascites. There is diffuse enhancement of the peritoneum and nodularity of the greater omentum (arrow). The visualized small bowel segments are fixed with mild dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g14c.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14c.</b>  Tuberculous peritonitis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) shows a caseating granuloma with a central area of necrotic acellular debris surrounded by histiocytes, some of which are multinucleated (arrow), and a variable number of lymphocytes. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; acid-fast bacillus [Ziehl-Neelsen] stain) reveals barely visible tuberculous organisms (arrows), which appear as small, thin, red bacilli. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan of a 22-year-old man who complained of intermittent fevers for 1 month and a new onset of abdominal pain shows loculated ascites. There is diffuse enhancement of the peritoneum and nodularity of the greater omentum (arrow). The visualized small bowel segments are fixed with mild dilatation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F14C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c15a.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Histoplasmosis peritonitis in a 31-year-old man with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows innumerable, predominantly intracellular spores of <i>Histoplasma</i> organisms. The spores are round to oval, measure 2–4 μm in diameter, and have a central or off-center blue-staining chromatic mass. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; Grocott methenamine silver stain) shows the dark staining, budding organisms. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows nodular soft-tissue infiltration of the greater omentum, asymmetric cecal wall thickening, and thickening of the terminal ileum and ileocecal valve with surrounding inflammatory change.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c15b.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Histoplasmosis peritonitis in a 31-year-old man with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows innumerable, predominantly intracellular spores of <i>Histoplasma</i> organisms. The spores are round to oval, measure 2–4 μm in diameter, and have a central or off-center blue-staining chromatic mass. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; Grocott methenamine silver stain) shows the dark staining, budding organisms. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows nodular soft-tissue infiltration of the greater omentum, asymmetric cecal wall thickening, and thickening of the terminal ileum and ileocecal valve with surrounding inflammatory change.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g15c.jpeg" height="1408" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15c.</b>  Histoplasmosis peritonitis in a 31-year-old man with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; H-E stain) shows innumerable, predominantly intracellular spores of <i>Histoplasma</i> organisms. The spores are round to oval, measure 2–4 μm in diameter, and have a central or off-center blue-staining chromatic mass. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; Grocott methenamine silver stain) shows the dark staining, budding organisms. <b>(c)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows nodular soft-tissue infiltration of the greater omentum, asymmetric cecal wall thickening, and thickening of the terminal ileum and ileocecal valve with surrounding inflammatory change.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F15C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g16a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Inflammatory pseudotumor in a 36-year-old man who complained of left flank pain, diarrhea, nausea, and vomiting. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a 6-cm soft-tissue attenuation mass in the small bowel mesentery that has central low attenuation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the resected surgical specimen shows the tan mass with central necrosis in the small bowel mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c16b.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Inflammatory pseudotumor in a 36-year-old man who complained of left flank pain, diarrhea, nausea, and vomiting. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a 6-cm soft-tissue attenuation mass in the small bowel mesentery that has central low attenuation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the resected surgical specimen shows the tan mass with central necrosis in the small bowel mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g17a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17a.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis in a liver transplant recipient who complained of bloating and symptoms of bowel obstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show encapsulation of the small bowel by a thickened and enhancing peritoneum (arrows in <b>b</b>). The small bowel is tethered in a radial configuration and has mural thickening. A small amount of ascites is present. <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative photographs show the thick, opaque peritoneum unopened <b>(c)</b> and opened <b>(d)</b>. (Case courtesy of Frank Scholz, MD, Lahey Clinic, Burlington, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F17A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g17b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17b.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis in a liver transplant recipient who complained of bloating and symptoms of bowel obstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show encapsulation of the small bowel by a thickened and enhancing peritoneum (arrows in <b>b</b>). The small bowel is tethered in a radial configuration and has mural thickening. A small amount of ascites is present. <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative photographs show the thick, opaque peritoneum unopened <b>(c)</b> and opened <b>(d)</b>. (Case courtesy of Frank Scholz, MD, Lahey Clinic, Burlington, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F17B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c17c.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F17C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17c.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis in a liver transplant recipient who complained of bloating and symptoms of bowel obstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show encapsulation of the small bowel by a thickened and enhancing peritoneum (arrows in <b>b</b>). The small bowel is tethered in a radial configuration and has mural thickening. A small amount of ascites is present. <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative photographs show the thick, opaque peritoneum unopened <b>(c)</b> and opened <b>(d)</b>. (Case courtesy of Frank Scholz, MD, Lahey Clinic, Burlington, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F17C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c17d.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F17D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17d.</b>  Sclerosing encapsulating peritonitis in a liver transplant recipient who complained of bloating and symptoms of bowel obstruction. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scans show encapsulation of the small bowel by a thickened and enhancing peritoneum (arrows in <b>b</b>). The small bowel is tethered in a radial configuration and has mural thickening. A small amount of ascites is present. <b>(c, d)</b> Intraoperative photographs show the thick, opaque peritoneum unopened <b>(c)</b> and opened <b>(d)</b>. (Case courtesy of Frank Scholz, MD, Lahey Clinic, Burlington, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F17D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g18a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18a.</b>  Endometriosis in the right subhepatic space in a 43-year-old woman who complained of intermittent right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a small low-signal-intensity mass in the right subhepatic space (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On an axial opposed phase T1-weighted fast multiplanar SPGR (spoiled gradient-recalled acquisition in the steady state) image, the lesion has high signal intensity with a low-signal-intensity rim (arrow). <b>(c)</b> On an axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with fat saturation, the lesion has low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image with fat saturation obtained during the portal venous phase of gadolinium enhancement shows that the lesion enhances (arrow). (Case courtesy of Frank Scholz, MD, Burlington, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F18A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g18b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18b.</b>  Endometriosis in the right subhepatic space in a 43-year-old woman who complained of intermittent right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a small low-signal-intensity mass in the right subhepatic space (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On an axial opposed phase T1-weighted fast multiplanar SPGR (spoiled gradient-recalled acquisition in the steady state) image, the lesion has high signal intensity with a low-signal-intensity rim (arrow). <b>(c)</b> On an axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with fat saturation, the lesion has low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image with fat saturation obtained during the portal venous phase of gadolinium enhancement shows that the lesion enhances (arrow). (Case courtesy of Frank Scholz, MD, Burlington, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F18B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g18c.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18c.</b>  Endometriosis in the right subhepatic space in a 43-year-old woman who complained of intermittent right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a small low-signal-intensity mass in the right subhepatic space (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On an axial opposed phase T1-weighted fast multiplanar SPGR (spoiled gradient-recalled acquisition in the steady state) image, the lesion has high signal intensity with a low-signal-intensity rim (arrow). <b>(c)</b> On an axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with fat saturation, the lesion has low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image with fat saturation obtained during the portal venous phase of gadolinium enhancement shows that the lesion enhances (arrow). (Case courtesy of Frank Scholz, MD, Burlington, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F18C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g18d.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18d.</b>  Endometriosis in the right subhepatic space in a 43-year-old woman who complained of intermittent right upper quadrant pain. <b>(a)</b> Axial T1-weighted image shows a small low-signal-intensity mass in the right subhepatic space (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On an axial opposed phase T1-weighted fast multiplanar SPGR (spoiled gradient-recalled acquisition in the steady state) image, the lesion has high signal intensity with a low-signal-intensity rim (arrow). <b>(c)</b> On an axial fast spin-echo T2-weighted image with fat saturation, the lesion has low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial T1-weighted image with fat saturation obtained during the portal venous phase of gadolinium enhancement shows that the lesion enhances (arrow). (Case courtesy of Frank Scholz, MD, Burlington, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F18D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g19a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F19A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19a.</b>  Gliomatosis peritonei in a 13-year-old girl who complained of abdominal pain, distention, and constipation. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans (<b>a</b> obtained at a more cephalic level than <b>b</b>) show a large, well-defined, complex cystic mass in the lower abdomen that contains fat and calcifications and extends into the upper abdomen. Ascites is present. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a complex solid and cystic mass that mimics cerebral tissue. The mass is admixed with fibrosis, fat, cartilaginous tissue, and bone, content similar to that of a teratoma. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph of the omentum shows innumerable tiny nodules of gliomatosis throughout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F19A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g19b.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F19B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19b.</b>  Gliomatosis peritonei in a 13-year-old girl who complained of abdominal pain, distention, and constipation. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans (<b>a</b> obtained at a more cephalic level than <b>b</b>) show a large, well-defined, complex cystic mass in the lower abdomen that contains fat and calcifications and extends into the upper abdomen. Ascites is present. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a complex solid and cystic mass that mimics cerebral tissue. The mass is admixed with fibrosis, fat, cartilaginous tissue, and bone, content similar to that of a teratoma. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph of the omentum shows innumerable tiny nodules of gliomatosis throughout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F19B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c19c.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F19C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19c.</b>  Gliomatosis peritonei in a 13-year-old girl who complained of abdominal pain, distention, and constipation. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans (<b>a</b> obtained at a more cephalic level than <b>b</b>) show a large, well-defined, complex cystic mass in the lower abdomen that contains fat and calcifications and extends into the upper abdomen. Ascites is present. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a complex solid and cystic mass that mimics cerebral tissue. The mass is admixed with fibrosis, fat, cartilaginous tissue, and bone, content similar to that of a teratoma. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph of the omentum shows innumerable tiny nodules of gliomatosis throughout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F19C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c19d.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F19D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19d.</b>  Gliomatosis peritonei in a 13-year-old girl who complained of abdominal pain, distention, and constipation. <b>(a, b)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scans (<b>a</b> obtained at a more cephalic level than <b>b</b>) show a large, well-defined, complex cystic mass in the lower abdomen that contains fat and calcifications and extends into the upper abdomen. Ascites is present. <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph shows a complex solid and cystic mass that mimics cerebral tissue. The mass is admixed with fibrosis, fat, cartilaginous tissue, and bone, content similar to that of a teratoma. <b>(d)</b> Intraoperative photograph of the omentum shows innumerable tiny nodules of gliomatosis throughout.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F19D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g20a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20a.</b>  Heterotopic ossification and osseous metaplasia in a 53-year-old man who sustained extensive abdominal injuries in a motor vehicle accident and underwent multiple laparotomies. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple, high-attenuation, branching and linear structures (arrows) in the small bowel mesentery and along the peritoneal surface. These structures extend into the open abdominal wall. <b>(b)</b> Intra-operative photograph shows an ossified fragment (arrow) being lifted out of the mesentery by forceps. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) of a histologic specimen shows benign, mature bone with lacunae. The bone has formed spicules and mature adipose tissue, and blood vessels are between the spicules, as is found in normal mature bone (ie, fatty marrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F20A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c20b.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F20B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20b.</b>  Heterotopic ossification and osseous metaplasia in a 53-year-old man who sustained extensive abdominal injuries in a motor vehicle accident and underwent multiple laparotomies. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple, high-attenuation, branching and linear structures (arrows) in the small bowel mesentery and along the peritoneal surface. These structures extend into the open abdominal wall. <b>(b)</b> Intra-operative photograph shows an ossified fragment (arrow) being lifted out of the mesentery by forceps. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) of a histologic specimen shows benign, mature bone with lacunae. The bone has formed spicules and mature adipose tissue, and blood vessels are between the spicules, as is found in normal mature bone (ie, fatty marrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F20B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c20c.jpeg" height="974" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F20C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20c.</b>  Heterotopic ossification and osseous metaplasia in a 53-year-old man who sustained extensive abdominal injuries in a motor vehicle accident and underwent multiple laparotomies. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple, high-attenuation, branching and linear structures (arrows) in the small bowel mesentery and along the peritoneal surface. These structures extend into the open abdominal wall. <b>(b)</b> Intra-operative photograph shows an ossified fragment (arrow) being lifted out of the mesentery by forceps. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) of a histologic specimen shows benign, mature bone with lacunae. The bone has formed spicules and mature adipose tissue, and blood vessels are between the spicules, as is found in normal mature bone (ie, fatty marrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F20C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07g21a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F21A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21a.</b>  Splenosis in a 47-year-old man with hepatitis C and cirrhosis who had undergone traumatic splenectomy at age 13 years. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple, lobular and round, homogeneously enhancing masses (arrows) in the anterior abdomen. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the resected omentum shows multiple foci of splenic tissue. Scale is in millimeters. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) shows abundant red pulp formed by numerous red blood cells within sinusoids and surrounding the white pulp. The white pulp resembles a lymphoid germinal center, with central B cells surrounded by T cells and each lymphoid aggregate is traversed by an arteriole.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F21A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c21b.jpeg" height="915" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F21B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21b.</b>  Splenosis in a 47-year-old man with hepatitis C and cirrhosis who had undergone traumatic splenectomy at age 13 years. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple, lobular and round, homogeneously enhancing masses (arrows) in the anterior abdomen. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the resected omentum shows multiple foci of splenic tissue. Scale is in millimeters. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) shows abundant red pulp formed by numerous red blood cells within sinusoids and surrounding the white pulp. The white pulp resembles a lymphoid germinal center, with central B cells surrounded by T cells and each lymphoid aggregate is traversed by an arteriole.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F21B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07c21c.jpeg" height="555" width="730" aria-labelledby="F21C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21c.</b>  Splenosis in a 47-year-old man with hepatitis C and cirrhosis who had undergone traumatic splenectomy at age 13 years. <b>(a)</b> Intravenous and oral contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple, lobular and round, homogeneously enhancing masses (arrows) in the anterior abdomen. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the resected omentum shows multiple foci of splenic tissue. Scale is in millimeters. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×4; H-E stain) shows abundant red pulp formed by numerous red blood cells within sinusoids and surrounding the white pulp. The white pulp resembles a lymphoid germinal center, with central B cells surrounded by T cells and each lymphoid aggregate is traversed by an arteriole.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.292085189&amp;id=F21C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 1.</b> <b>Classification of Secondary Tumors and Tumorlike Lesions of the Peritoneum</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07t01x.jpeg" height="1777" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T1" loading="lazy" /></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T2" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 2.</b> <b>Classification of Primary Tumors of the Peritoneum</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.292085189/asset/images/g09mr07t02x.jpeg" height="1401" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T2" loading="lazy" /></figure></div><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Meyers</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">MA</span></span>, Oliphant M, Berne AS, Feldberg MA. The peritoneal ligaments and mesenteries: pat