<div class="core-journal-description"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">29</span></span> • <span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">2</span></span> • <span property="datePublished">Mar 1 2009</span></div><div class="core-pagination"><span class="heading">Pages</span>: <span class="content"><span property="pageStart">347</span> - <span property="pageEnd">373</span></span></div><div class="core-pmid"><span class="heading">PubMed</span>: <a class="content" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19325052/" property="sameAs" target="_blank" title="Link to PubMed">19325052</a></div></div></div></section><section class="core-copyright"><h4>Copyright</h4><div role="paragraph">© 2009.</div></section><section class="core-history"><h4>History</h4><div><b class="core-label">Published online</b>: Mar 1 2009</div></section><section class="core-permissions"><h4>Permissions</h4><div>Request permissions for this article.</div><div><a class="btn" href="https://marketplace.copyright.com/rs-ui-web/mp/search/all/10.1148%2Frg.292085189">Request Permissions</a></div></section><section property="keywords"><h4>Keywords</h4><ol><li><a href="/action/doSearch?AllField=FDG+%3D+fluorine+18+fluoro-2-deoxy-d-glucose&amp;stemming=yes&amp;publication=radiographics" alt="Search on this keyword" rel="nofollow">FDG = fluorine 18 fluoro-2-deoxy-<span data-style="small-caps">d</span>-glucose</a></li><li><a href="/action/doSearch?AllField=H-E+%3D+hematoxylin-eosin&amp;stemming=yes&amp;publication=radiographics" alt="Search on this keyword" rel="nofollow">H-E = hematoxylin-eosin</a></li></ol></section><section class="core-article-notes"><h4>Notes</h4><div role="paragraph">The clinical, pathologic, and imaging features of secondary peritoneal tumors and tumorlike lesions are reviewed, with emphasis on the anatomic features of the peritoneal cavity that affect the pattern of disease involvement.</div></section></section><section id="tab-contributors" role="tabpanel"><h3>Authors</h3><section class="core-authors"><h4>Affiliations</h4><div id="con1" property="author" typeof="Person"><div class="heading"><span property="givenName">Angela D.</span> <span property="familyName">Levy</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">COL, MC, USA</span></div><div class="content"><div class="affiliations"><div property="affiliation" typeof="Organization"><span property="name">From the Department of Radiology and Radiological Sciences, Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences, 4301 Jones Bridge Rd, Bethesda, MD 20814-4799 (A.D.L.); and Departments of Radiologic Pathology (A.D.L.) and Hepatic and Gastrointestinal Pathology (J.C.S., L.H.S.), Armed Forces Institute of Pathology, Washington, DC. Received August 4, 2008; revision requested September 8 and received September 17; accepted September 24. L.H.S. is a stockholder in Bristol-Myers-Squibb and IBM; all other authors have no financial relationships to disclose.</span></div></div><div class="core-author-link"><a href="/authored-by/Levy/Angela+D" rel="nofollow">View all articles by this author</a></div></div></div><div id="con2" property="author" typeof="Person"><div class="heading"><span property="givenName">Janet C.</span> <span property="familyName">Shaw</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">Lt Col, USAF, MC</span></div><div class="content"><div class="affiliations"><div property="affiliation" typeof="Organization"><span property="name">From the Department of Radiology and Radiological Sciences, Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences, 4301 Jones Bridge Rd, Bethesda, MD 20814-4799 (A.D.L.); and Departments of Radiologic Pathology (A.D.L.) and Hepatic and Gastrointestinal Pathology (J.C.S., L.H.S.), Armed Forces Institute of Pathology, Washington, DC. Received August 4, 2008; revision req